# Editing Telegram code (`submodules/**`)

Upstream Telegram-iOS code that we periodically re-merge. Follow the change
ladder in `AGENTS.md` (prefer not editing Telegram code at all). When you must
add or change code here, mark it so it survives the next merge.

## Nicegram markers

- Open every Nicegram addition with `// Nicegram {FeatureName}`; close a
  multi-line block with a bare `//` on its own line:

```swift
// Nicegram Voice Typing
private var voiceTypingHostingController: UIViewController?
//
```

- To modify an existing upstream line, put a marker directly above it describing
  the change:

```swift
// Nicegram downloading feature, 'accountContext, shouldSave' params added
return fetchManager.interactivelyFetched(/* ... */, accountContext: accountContext, shouldSave: false)
```

- Reuse the SAME `{FeatureName}` across every touch-point of one feature (e.g.
  `AiChat`, `Voice Typing`, `SensitiveContentAccess`, `downloading feature`) so
  they are greppable together.
- Never leave an unmarked diff in `submodules/**`.
- Put whole new Nicegram files under a `Nicegram/` subfolder of the submodule
  (e.g. `submodules/TelegramUI/Sources/Nicegram/...`), not loose beside upstream
  files, and update the module's `BUILD`/`BUCK` target.

## Reactive: bridge SSignalKit, don't spread it

Telegram uses `SwiftSignalKit.Signal`. Convert at the boundary and keep new logic
in `async`/`await` + Combine (helpers in
`submodules/SSignalKit/SwiftSignalKit/Source/`):

- Signal → async: `signal.awaitForFirstValue()`, `signal.awaitForCompletion()`,
  `signal.asyncStream(_:)`.
- async → Signal: `Signal.awaitThrowingOperation { ... }`,
  `Signal.awaitOperation { ... }`.
- Signal ↔ Combine: `signal.toPublisher()`, `publisher.toSignal()`,
  `signal.skipError()`, `AnyCancellable(disposable)`.
